text: saturday morning found me in a thornton park @starbucks with one of my best friends, her fiancÃ©, and their wedding photographers. amidst the excitement of their upcoming ceremony and our discussion around day-of specifics, i grabbed the @nytimes and was pleased to see an article written regarding ryan adamsâ€™ album cancellation. although this issue has been given new life and new light in recent months thanks to the incredible #metoo and #timesup movements, itâ€™s as important as ever to acknowledge that this reckoning has been brewing for decades now, spurred on by the defiance of honest and brave survivors who were demanding justice and accountability back when this issue was still overwhelmingly kept in the dark. today, we are able to follow those footpaths and forge the future of justice. we have a long journey ahead in the fight for justice for survivors of sexual abuse and we know that journey will include both the good and bad days, but yesterday was a good one. the wider the conversation spreads, the higher the demand for accountability will beâ€”and the sooner justice will be served.

text:
the next time you think, "why does god let bad things happen?" think about this...
-
jesus was two miles away from lazarus when he heard his friend was sick. two miles. he could've been there in about forty minutes. twenty if he ran. instead he waited two days before he began his journey. when he finally showed up, his friend had been dead, in the grave, for four days.
-
why?
-
"it is for godâ€™s glory so that godâ€™s son may be glorified through it.â€ still, he wept over what had happened because he loved his friend dearly. he still cared about what his people were going through. jesus wept. the shortest verse in the bible makes the biggest impact because he still weeps for us.
-
jesus weeps for us for when we get dumped.
jesus weeps for us when we get bullied.
jesus weeps for us when we feel lonely and hopeless.
jesus weeps for us when we lose a baby.
jesus weeps for the children in africa, india, and thailand.
jesus weeps for the orphans and widows.
jesus weeps for the ones who just received bad news from their doctor.
jesus weeps for the mother who buries her son.
jesus weeps for anyone with claim to the #metoo movement.
jesus weeps for the girl in the high school bathroom who feels like she doesn't have options.
jesus weeps for the boy who is too afraid to speak up because his father might beat him again.
jesus weeps for you.
jesus loves you so much that he weeps for you when you struggle, when you hurt, when you don't understand.

.
.
.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
christopher wylie, who worked with a cambridge university academic to obtain the data, told the observer: â€œwe exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles. and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.â€ documents seen by the observer, and confirmed by a facebook statement, show that by late 2015 the company had found out that information had been harvested on an unprecedented scale. however, at the time it failed to alert users and took only limited steps to recover and secure the private information of more than 50 million individuals.

the data was collected through an app called thisisyourdigitallife, built by academic aleksandr kogan, separately from his work at cambridge university. through his company global science research (gsr), in collaboration with cambridge analytica, hundreds of thousands of users were paid to take a personality test and agreed to have their data collected for academic use.

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takersâ€™ facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebookâ€™s â€œplatform policyâ€ allowed only collection of friendsâ€™ data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for advertising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebookâ€™s role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robert mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate â€œinformation warfareâ€ against the us.

carole cadwalladr & emma graham-harrison
the guardian

text:
reporting a rapist is a personal decision.
a campus administrator once said to me in regard to why i was pursuing a legal case against my rapist, "i understand you are coming forward because you don't want him to hurt others." while this seems like a nice sentiment, it's not. it places responsibility on me for his actions.
i am doing this for me. i am doing this so i can get justice for what happened to me. i had a right to choose what path was right for me and in the end that was coming forward. but i also had the right to choose to not report my rape. his actions are not contingent upon my silence. i refuse to bear the burden and responsibility of his past and future actions. 
we need to stop placing responsibility on victims and start placing responsibilities on rapists. considering the reality of our justice system, it is understandable that many survivors don't come forward. 
so no, i did not come forward to protect others. i am doing this for me. 
survivors have enough responsibility to bear, they don't need to bear the responsibility of their rapists' actions too. this doesn't mean that the chance of others being victimized wasn't a factor in my decision, it just means that survivors shouldn't be pressured into doing something that is not right for them just because others might be hurt.

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytica until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

cnn

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. heâ€™s the only straight man iâ€™ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

text:
when i wanted to report my rape to the police, i spoke on the phone with an police officer. and i do absolutely respect and support the police and i really donâ€™t want to talk them down or anything... but they really dissappointed me in my case. 
so i was on the phone with the police officer, and i told him what had happened and that i wanted to report it. after hearing my story, the officer told me that it would be useless to report it because there wasnâ€™t really enough evidence for them to investigate. 
this made me feel so unimportant.. almost as if it wasnâ€™t important enough for them to start an investigation... they didnâ€™t even try to get security cameras or anything.... i felt like i was being dramatic and just had to get over myself and move on. 
being honest, i think that if i wouldâ€™ve actually reported the crime, it would have helped me â€œmove onâ€. that way i could at least feel like i could have a chance to get justice. or that i was important enough to conduct an investigation for.
i am so sad to think that this is still a reality nowadays... #mentalhealthawareness #metoo #rapesurvivor #ptsdawareness #ptsdrecovery

final week is how to use everything and anything as a weapon or equaliser or to aid your defence, and basics of weapons defence. 
if you want to drop in for one of these topics please do itâ€™s Â£25 on the door.

i'm very blessed to be able to do my part to help empower and instill a sense of confidence and security in women, while downloading my concepts and practical experience from not only a lifetime of martial arts, but also over a decade in security & protection.
doing this for not only my community, but for those who live and work outside of it, is both fulfilling  and serious work.

text: ivy muslim conference 2019âœŒğŸ¾the past two days were a emotional roller coaster. i enjoyed sharing a ~4 hr (each way) van ride, coffee break at barnes and nobles, getting jealous of yale students for having amazing food options, fitting 6 people on a common room floor, listening to the inspiring journey of @mokhtar_alkhanshali , eating at @thehalalguys ,listening to love poetries, taking a bathroom break at the spookiest welcome house with these amazing people! there were moments of discomfort and rage: a #metoo discussion table with all male students, a conservative speaker spewing hate but getting a leeway only because she is a woman, not having the opportunity to have constructive debate! after all the anxiety and laughter, i have learned a lot alhamdulillah and have reaffirmed my passion to serve the marginalized communities: gender-based violence survivors, lgbtq+ community, people with mental health issues. i hope the next conference will be more welcoming of these minority groups and create opportunities for constructive discussions.

text:
the thing about sex, as far back as ancient egypt, is that *women* had as much ownership over desire as men, which later met it's demise in the victorian era, and never really regained it's footing
.

its alarming that people have become so simple as to *charge* men with the belief that these behaviors can exist in singularity, when no such thing is humanly possible
.

enter the grotesquely ignorant white lady #metoo movement: conversations about personal comfort erected next to conversations about rape, sex and molestation, all of which are indicative of grave mental illness
.

i just imagine meg newman and meg mantia (that ignorant, untrained food photographer) scapegoating the greater world bc they're culturally, sexually, illiterate, shaming anyone who dares to complicate human discourse
.

it's pathetic, it's white, and it's up from a brief history that *also* doesn't allow bike riding
.

white people, particularly white girls -- into their 60s!!, are *collectively* problematic in their *own* assumptions of their lasting ingenuity, bc although it's become an internalized implicit psychology, its nothing more then a *currency*, exchanged for a unique brand of culturally exclusive american protection, which begins with sexuality (think white men hanging black men on behalf of saving american purity, personified in the innocent white girl)
.

white girls, like carol from the housewives, truly believe that harvey winstiens (sp?) mention of "cumming when his nipples are rubbed" is equal to cases of *childhood rape*. why does she believe this? because she's a misogynist, activating white male sexism to both exoticize and protect her, depending on her mood
.

it's sick, but far more then that? it's learned
.

white girls can't be uncomfortable. they think it's an inherent right to find universal, unchallenged safety in the world. it's gross, and a full denial of a base respect expected of an adult on behalf of cultural diversity -- yes, sexuality is cultural
.

it's like meg newman and her *need* to publish the same book over and over again til her relationship to her sense of comfort becomes militia. it's tacky, and it's not at all aligned with power, but fear

text:
ho il piacere di annunciarti le prossime date del mio nuovo seminario

come liberarsi da una relazione tossica - mestre 3 marzo - roma 28 aprile - milano 5 maggio

a mestre si terrÃ  dunque domenica 3 marzo presso il centro invita
via impastato 28 orario: 09.30 - 13.30, 14.30 - 18.30

il programma del seminario sarÃ  prevalentemente esperienziale, 
con esercitazioni individuali in gruppo specifiche,
pensate per affrontare le varie fasi di una relazione tossica.

ecco in sintesi gli obiettivi della giornata: - identificare dei comportamenti tipici del manipolatore affettivo
- prendere coscienza di ciÃ² che si cerca in amore
- andare oltre il dolore dei ricordi traumatici
- superare la paura di non farcela da soli

text:
hi friends

iâ€™m going silent for a lil while to process everything thatâ€™s happened in the past year. i hid so much from so many people. 
a year ago this week, i was sexually assaulted. i was scared into silence and truly felt that no one would believe me. my inability to process what happened led to a serious drinking problem and prescription drug abuse - i detailed it in an essay you can find on my website if thatâ€™s your thing. 
this picture was taken the very next week, if i recall correctly. donâ€™t assume that because someoneâ€™s outwardly flowering that theyâ€™re not withering inside.

iâ€™m going to just put my head down and focus on myself for the first time in a long while. itâ€™s fun and all to break it until it breaks. it broke. letâ€™s fix it

lots of love and endless blessings to all of you wonderful people. keep the faith. play the long game. #metoo

text:
"for us and for our salvation he came down from heaven, was incarnate of the holy spirit and the virgin mary and became truly human. for our sake he was crucified under pontius pilate; he suffered death and was buried. on the third day he rose again in accordance with the scriptures; he ascended into heaven and is seated at the right hand of the father. he will come again in glory to judge the living and the dead, and his kingdom will have no end." -a segment of the nicene creed

as i read this i'm reminded as i was by last week's reflection on the nicene creed, of god's immanence- his nearness. both the incarnation and the indwelling of the holy spirit profoundly reflect to me god's love for us and his desire to be near us. these truths are such beautiful and moving aspects of christian theology!

i'm also reminded of phillippians 2- paul's powerful description of jesus, who is god himself, becoming human and suffering for our salvation.

these days, because of #metoo, #churchtoo, black lives matter and some of my personal experiences, issues related to power are often on my mind. for me, the incarnation, as reflected in philippians 2, is the ultimate tribute to the importance and power of humility and servant leadership in the church. i hope this reality would cause those of us who stray from christ's humble, sacrificial example to repent and return to the path he laid out for us in this regard.

text:
*not slimmingworld related.. sorry* ... i never talk about this but i need to and i hope people on here can be understanding... today, i saw him. i saw the 'man' that ruined my youth, ruined my sanity, my life for the past nearly 8 years. i walked past the person that took my innocence, who lead me to a path of self-hatred and guilt, being bullied, anxiety, low mood. but, did he even look at me? no, because to him i'm nothing. i haven't changed his life, i didn't take anything from him. that's what made me so angry, angry enough to write this post. why have i spent 8 years suffering because of someone who i am nothing to? he may have caused me 8 years of pain but i'm damned if he's going to cause me another 8 years. one day i plan to report it, not when i'm 'brave enough' or 'strong enough' but when i'm ready. i dont really know why ive decided to open myself up right now, but im sick of hiding. i just wanted to put this out here and thank you for reading part of my story â¤
.
.
.
.
. .
#metoo #mentalhealth #1in4mentalhealth #1in5 #strong #brave #unite #powerfulwoman #loveyourself #itstime #mystory #womenpower #selfcare #selfworth #empower
